postcontent:
I have acquired through trade an antique DWM 1916 Luger Pistol in the rarer .30 cal configuration.

The antique weapon has signs of age, and more than likely saw action in WW1 and possibly WW2. Not in perfect condition and price reflects value.

THE GOOD: The best thing, and why it is relatively valuable: all serial numbers match and this antique weapon is 100% original, even down to the real wood grips. The Germans were very meticulous about serial numbers, and gave virtually every piece of this weapon a serial. We can disassemble together if you want to verify.

THE BAD: One hand grip is missing a screw. I know of a website where you can order original Luger parts and they have original screws in stock, I'll buy them for you, or you can supply your own and deduct your costs from the purchase price (as long as it's less than $50)

THE UGLY: The ammunition for this antique weapon can be expensive, Fiocci starts at $25 or so per box, Winchester is about $55. I wouldn't shoot it, consider this a rare antique and if you blow it up trying to fire it, well, sorry for ya.

Grab a great deal and a piece of military history at a great bargain. $700 negotiable, willing to work with the highest offer. Call Wes @ (318) two one eight 6015 to view or inquire.

Stoeger now produces Cougars in 9x19mm, .45 ACP, and .40 S&W. Only the full size models are being produced

Prior to its acquisition by Beretta, Stoeger was located in New Jersey. Stoeger commissioned various small companies in Germany to manufacture a replica of the Luger, which it imported. It later sold an American-made version of the Luger in 1994. The pistol was all stainless steel and was in 9 m/m and sold as the American Eagle Luger with 4" and 6" barrels. postcontent:
My gunsmith and friend was making a custom 308 from scratch.  He said he'd could get a better deal by making a few at once.  I ordered two, now realize I only need one.  So I'm entertaining trades for one of these.

These are both Mauser actions.  Both have the metal finished in Duracoat.  The barrels are new sporter barrels and have fewer than 20 rounds through each.  Each has been glass bedded, and the barrels are free floated.  The triggers are original mauser, but have been lightened.
